==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la}} {{term|abductus||lang=la}}, perfect passive participle of {{term|abduco|abdūcō|lang=la|take away; seduce}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/æbˈdʌkt/}}
* {{rhymes|ʌkt}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{transitive}} To [[take away]] [[secretly]] by force; to [[carry away]] (a human being) [[wrongfully]] and usually by [[violence]]; to [[kidnap]].
#*{{quote-book
|year=1904
|author=Jules Verne
|title=The Master of the World
|chapter=16
|url=http://ebooks.adelaide.edu.au/v/verne/jules/v52mw/chapter16.html
|passage=That same night he had by force abducted the president and the secretary of the club, and had taken them, much against their will upon a voyage in the wonderful air-ship, the “Albatross,” which he had constructed.}}
# {{transitive|anatomy}} To [[draw away]], as a limb or other part, from its ordinary position.

